{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507853"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:58:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:58:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2677"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2677"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.05,0.16,0.11,0.37]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2677"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79026"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2677"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2677"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64375"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"527"},{"type":"tags","id":"917"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3224"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3229"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3302"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27066"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79026","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79026"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 52-year-old man presents with a five-day history of lower abdominal pain. The pain was initially intermittent and has now become constant. He has no other symptoms apart from some intermittent nausea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the patient\u0027s blood pressure is 115/90 mmHg, pulse 100/min and temperature 37.8\u00baC. Abdominal examination shows tenderness in the right iliac fossa and no other abnormalities. A CT scan is performed and shown below (Image):\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Colonoscopy and biopsy","CT-guided biopsy","Laparoscopy and biopsy","Right hemicolectomy","Broad-spectrum antibiotics"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows a mass in the right iliac fossa, immediately posterior to the caecum (Image). Taken together with the patient\u0027s five day history of lower abdominal pain, this is an appendix mass. Treatment should start with \u003Cstrong\u003Ebroad-spectrum antibiotics.\u003C/strong\u003E In most instances, the administration of broad-spectrum antibiotics will resolve the situation and an elective appendicectomy would be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT-guided biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate when investigating a mass of the large bowel especially to rule in or out bowel cancer. Neither the presentation nor CT scan suggests this as a differential. However, once this acute episode has been resolved it may be useful to check if the patient is actively participating in the bowel screening program as he is over 50 years of age. Very occasionally appendicitis may be precipitated by a mass in the caecum obstructing the appendices lumen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy and biopsy \u003C/strong\u003Eare incorrect for the same reason as CT-guided biopsy described above.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopy and biopsy \u003C/strong\u003Eare not appropriate for this presentation as initial management. If there was a concern of gangrenous or ruptured acute appendix then surgical intervention may be required \u00b1 any biopsies of suspicious lesions found.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight hemicolectomy \u003C/strong\u003Eis a common surgical procedure for the treatment of bowel cancer, specifically occupying the ascending colon. There is no evidence of cancer in this presentation or CT and further investigation would be required before performing such a procedure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Broad-spectrum antibiotics should be first line management for patients presenting with an appendix mass.","An appendix mass can often be managed conservatively with antibiotics, avoiding immediate surgery."],"references":["Demetrashvili Z, Kenchadze G, Pipia I, Ekaladze E, Kamkamidze G. Management of Appendiceal Mass and Abscess. An 11-Year Experience. Int Surg. 2015 Jun;100(6):1021-5. doi: 10.9738/INTSURG-D-14-00179.1. PMID: 26414824; PMCID: PMC4587501. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4587501/","Qian S, Vasileiou G, Dodgion C, Ray-Zack MD, Zakrison T, Rattan R, Namias N, Yeh DD; EAST Appendicitis Study Group. Narrow- versus Broad-Spectrum Antibiotics for Simple Acute Appendicitis Treated by Appendectomy: A Post Hoc Analysis of EAST MUSTANG Study. J Surg Res. 2020 Oct;254:217-222. doi: 10.1016/j.jss.2019.04.007. Epub 2020 May 28. PMID: 32474194. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32474194/","Moris D, Paulson EK, Pappas TN. Diagnosis and Management of Acute Appendicitis in Adults: A Review. JAMA. 2021 Dec 14;326(22):2299-2311. doi: 10.1001/jama.2021.20502. PMID: 34905026. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34905026/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64375"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2677"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15285"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20387"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15285","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15285"},"att